sentence: Patch to handle template instantiation error recovery:; The current class SavePendingInstantiationsRAII ([L8109 -L8125](https://github.com/root-project/root/blob/a402af862ace9573193500bcccaa8b4d56cc6632/interpreter/llvm/src/tools/clang/include/clang/Sema/Sema.h#L8109)) in clang/Sema.h which is called from cling/InterpreterParser.cpp [L920](https://github.com/root-project/root/blob/a402af862ace9573193500bcccaa8b4d56cc6632/interpreter/cling/lib/Interpreter/IncrementalParser.cpp#L920) can be replaced with the following patch in Sema.h; ```class PerformPendingInstantiationsRAII {; Sema &S;; public:; PerformPendingInstantiationsRAII(Sema &S): S(S) {} ;. ~PerformPendingInstantiationsRAII() {; S.PerformPendingInstantiations();; assert(S.PendingInstantiations.empty() &&; "there shouldn't be any pending instantiations");; }; };; ```; ; Change in InterpreterParser.cpp L902:; ```Sema::PerformPendingInstantiationsRAII PerformPendingInstantiations(S);```

author: root-project

sentence: > @hahnjo, I had the impression you fixed a similar issue in llvm mainline? Could you help with this here?. No, I only changed the way CUDA modules are registered and removed an unused argument: https://reviews.llvm.org/D123370; On top, I still can't run any CUDA code from within Clang (neither `master` nor `llvm13`) with my installed CUDA 11.7. It's probably too recent to work, but it means I cannot help debugging much (except making sure that CodeGen doesn't crash, which it shouldn't anymore, hopefully)...

sentence: > Hi folks. Is this PR at a point where I could try it with cling on Linux? I'd be happy to report any issues; for some compatibility issues, I can't use the stable cling's llvm so I've been eager watching the progress here.; > ; > If it's workable now, any tips for getting this hooked up to cling would be much appreciated. Either way, thanks so much for the huge effort to get llvm 13 in here. Hi @jeaye, we seem to be mostly converging. We know that some tests from cling's test suite still fail. If you cannot wait another month maybe it is now a good time to try it. . You can build cling against llvm13 using the llvm13 branches from clang.git and llvm.git available in my GitHub profile.

sentence: Thanks for the tip! Adding `-fno-rtti` to cling works, but only in the case where the function is defined inline in the header. When the function is defined in a separate TU which is linked into the host application, cling fails to find the symbol. I've updated the test case here: https://github.com/jeaye/cling-linkage-error-test-case. Basically just moved `test::integer::to_string` into its own cpp file, which then brings the linker errors back when trying to call it from cling.

sentence: Thanks for the tip! Adding `-fno-rtti` to cling works, but only in the case where the function is defined inline in the header. When the function is defined in a separate TU which is linked into the host application, cling fails to find the symbol. I've updated the test case here: https://github.com/jeaye/cling-linkage-error-test-case. Basically just moved `test::integer::to_string` into its own cpp file, which then brings the linker errors back when trying to call it from cling.
author: root-project
